If you cannot restart, we must manually break the deadlock by tricking the Directory Server (DS) into accepting the connections it currently has blocked.
The installer is stuck at [7/10] because it has disabled network listeners (nsslapd-allow-unauthenticated-binds: off or similar "lockdown" settings), but the CA service (Dogtag) must connect to LDAP via the network (Port 636) to finish the upgrade.
The "Live Fix" to Unstick the Installer
Perform these steps in a separate terminal while the installer is still sitting at [7/10]:
Force-Enable Listeners: The installer likely modified the DS configuration to block external access. We need to tell the Directory Server to listen again immediately.
bash
ldapmodify -x -h localhost -p 389 -D "cn=directory manager" -W <<EOF
dn: cn=config
changetype: modify
replace: nsslapd-listenhost
nsslapd-listenhost: 0.0.0.0
-
replace: nsslapd-ignore-wait-before-shutdown
nsslapd-ignore-wait-before-shutdown: on
EOF
Use code with caution.

(If it asks for a password, use the Directory Manager password you set at the start of the install).
Restart the Directory Server Service: Since the installer is waiting on the "Upgrading" task, restarting the service might kick the internal state machine.
bash
systemctl restart dirsrv@IPA-CALIX-LOCAL.service
Use code with caution.

Check the CA (Dogtag) Port: The error you saw earlier was "Connection Refused" on port 636. Check if anything is listening there now:
bash
ss -tulpn | grep 636
Use code with caution.

Watch the Installer Log: Immediately after the restart, run:
bash
tail -f /var/log/ipaupgrade.log
Use code with caution.

